04742nam a22006975i 9780814790908DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20042004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147909087 a10.18574/nyu/97808147909082doi  a(DE-B1597)548116  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPJ4545b.H58 2004 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a492.4/092221 aHoffman, Joel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn the Beginning :bA Short History of the Hebrew Language /cJoel Hoffman. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I Getting Started -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tChapter 2 Rules of the Game -- tPart II Antiquity -- tChapter 3 Writing -- tChapter 4 Magic Letters and the Name of God -- tChapter 5 The Masoretes -- tChapter 6 Pronunciation -- tPart III Moving On -- tChapter 7 The Dead Sea Scrolls -- tChapter 8 Dialects in the Bible -- tChapter 9 Post-Biblical Hebrew -- tPart IV Now -- tChapter 10 Modern Hebrew -- tChapter 11 Keep Your Voice from Weeping -- tPart V Appendices -- tAppendix A More about the Rules of the Game -- tAppendix B Further Reading -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHebrew as a language is just over 3,000 years old, and the story of its alphabet is unique among the languages of the world. Hebrew set the stage for almost every modern alphabet, and was arguably the first written language simple enough for everyone, not just scribes, to learn, making it possible to make a written record available to the masses for the first time. Written language has existed for so many years-since around 3500 BCE-that most of us take it for granted. But as Hoffman reveals in this entertaining and informative work, even the idea that speech can be divided into units called “words” and that these words can be represented with marks on a page, had to be discovered. As Hoffman points out, almost every modern system of writing descends from Hebrew; by studying the history of this language, we can learn a good deal about how we express ourselves today.Hoffman follows and decodes the adventure that is the history of Hebrew, illuminating how the written record has survived, the significance of the Dead Sea Scrolls and ancient translations, and attempts to determine how the language actually sounded. He places these developments into a historical context, and shows their continuing impact on the modern world.This sweeping history traces Hebrew's development as one of the first languages to make use of vowels. Hoffman also covers the dramatic story of the rebirth of Hebrew as a modern, spoken language.Packed with lively information about language and linguistics and history, In the Beginning is essential reading for both newcomers and scholars interested in learning more about Hebrew and languages in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aHebrew languagexHistory. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  adelightful.  ahistory.  alanguages.  alucid.  aoldest.  aworlds.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814790908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814790908/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-a